---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const blogContent = `
<p>The March 16 post ended with something like a vow: "We're building an engine
that learns what to search." The honest addendum is that the engine we had on
March 16 was still, fundamentally, <em>guessing</em>. It could pivot. It had
memory. But when it got stuck, it tried the same category of thing harder —
more SA iterations, higher temperature, a slightly different cooling schedule.</p>

<p>The last two days were about changing that. We gave the engine the ability to
panic usefully: to recognize when a strategy isn't just failing but is
<em>structurally</em> incapable of succeeding, and to reach for a fundamentally
different kind of mathematics.</p>

<h2>Problem 1: The SA Basin Trap</h2>

<p>After the circulant UNSAT result, we moved to unconstrained SA on K<sub>35</sub>.
Workers converged — and then stopped converging. The best energy would drop to
E = 12 or 13 and plateau. The existing reheat formula had a hard cap:</p>

<pre><code>newT = Math.min(2.0, staleCount) * baseT</code></pre>

<p>Once <code>staleCount</code> hit 2, the temperature ceiling was fixed. The worker
bounced endlessly around the bottom of the same crater — what we started calling
a <em>sterile basin</em>.</p>

<p>We replaced the capped reheat with a multi-stage escalation:</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Supercritical Reheats (4 stages):</strong> Temperature spikes scale
  unboundedly — T×1.4, T×1.8, T×2.2, T×2.6. Each stage resets a per-worker
  <code>escapeFails</code> counter. If the worker escapes (best energy improves),
  the counter resets. The escalation only continues if the worker fails to escape
  each time.</li>
  <li><strong>Graph Scatter:</strong> If all 4 reheat stages fail, the worker is
  teleported to a completely random starting graph. Not a mutation — a full
  stochastic restart from a new random adjacency matrix. Energy spikes back to
  E ≈ 800. The idea: a sterile crater that survives 4 supercritical reheats is
  too deep to escape by temperature alone. Randomize out.</li>
</ol>

<p>The result is visible in the SA logs now: <code>[SA] Basin sterile after 4 reheats.
SCATTERING to new coordinates. E=812</code>. Workers thrash for a while after scatter,
but they avoid permanently sleeping in bad basins.</p>

<h2>Problem 2: The ARCHITECT's Conceptual Basin</h2>

<p>The SA basin problem has an exact analogue at the LLM layer. On repeated
failures, the ARCHITECT was receiving the same context at the same temperature
and producing subtle variations of the same strategy. More SA iterations. A
different cooling rate. It was a conceptual local minimum.</p>

<p>We implemented escalating creativity as a three-stage ladder keyed to consecutive
macro-failure count in the ResearchJournal:</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr><th>Stage</th><th>Failures</th><th>Temperature</th><th>Directive</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>1 — INITIAL TRIAGE</td><td>0–2</td><td>0.20</td><td>Analyze the mathematical depth. Consider advanced frameworks from the start.</td></tr>
<tr><td>2 — LOCAL MINIMUM DETECTED</td><td>3–5</td><td>0.70</td><td>Direct combinatorial search has failed. Pivot to structural approaches.</td></tr>
<tr><td>3 — CONCEPTUAL SCATTER</td><td>≥6</td><td>0.95</td><td>Abandon direct calculation. Translate to a continuous or algebraic domain.</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>Stage 3 is what we call the Wiles Maneuver — named for Andrew Wiles's proof of
Fermat's Last Theorem, which worked by translating a discrete number theory
problem into the continuous language of elliptic curves and modular forms. When
the engine enters Stage 3, the ARCHITECT is explicitly instructed to do the
same: stop thinking about edge colorings and start thinking about spectral
properties, algebraic symmetry groups, or semidefinite programming relaxations.</p>

<h2>Problem 3: 25 SKILLs, 3 Bridge Frameworks</h2>

<p>The escalation ladder only works if the ARCHITECT knows what to escalate
<em>to</em>. We built a library of 25 mathematical proof techniques as
<code>SKILL.md</code> files — structured documentation that the engine retrieves
via RAG and injects as context into the ARCHITECT's planning step.</p>

<p>The three most important are the bridge frameworks — techniques that translate
discrete combinatorial problems into continuous, algebraic, or spectral domains:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Algebraic Graph Construction:</strong> Instead of randomly sampling
  graphs, construct them from Cayley graphs over finite groups or quadratic
  residues (Paley graphs). These have built-in algebraic symmetry and known
  spectral properties. The Exoo R(4,6) witness from 1989 is a Paley graph — the
  SAT solver doesn't know this, but the SKILL does.</li>

  <li><strong>Spectral Graph Bounds:</strong> The Hoffman bound and Lovász theta
  function translate clique/independent set existence into eigenvalue inequalities.
  Instead of asking "does this graph contain a K_4?" you ask "is the largest
  eigenvalue compatible with K_4 absence?" The spectral perspective gives the SA
  energy function smooth gradients instead of integer jumps.</li>

  <li><strong>Razborov's Flag Algebras:</strong> A method for converting finite
  subgraph counting into infinite continuous density matrices, solvable by
  Semidefinite Programming. Used to prove tight asymptotic bounds on graph
  densities. For Ramsey problems, this gives certified upper bounds — we may not
  find a witness, but we can prove exactly how large the minimum violation must be.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Problem 4: The ARCHITECT Wasn't Actually Running</h2>

<p>We shipped all of this and ran a 7-hour search. Then we looked at the logs:</p>

<pre><code>⚠️ [Architect.formulateDAG] attempt 1/3: JSON Parse error: Unrecognized token '\`'
⚠️ [Architect.formulateDAG] attempt 2/3: JSON Parse error: Unrecognized token '\`'
⚠️ [Architect.formulateDAG] attempt 3/3: JSON Parse error: Unrecognized token '\`'
⚠️ [DAG] formulateDAG failed — falling back to flat pivot</code></pre>

<p>Every single pivot. Every attempt. The Proof DAG planner — the entire ARCHITECT
layer — was dead. The engine had been running naive flat SA pivots for seven hours,
completely bypassing the DAG, the escalation ladder, and the SKILL library.</p>

<p>The bug: our <code>extractJSON()</code> function used a regex with <code>^</code>
and <code>$</code> anchors:</p>

<pre><code>/^&grave;&grave;&grave;(?:json)?\\s*\\n?([\\s\\S]*?)\\n?\\s*&grave;&grave;&grave;$/</code></pre>

<p>Gemini 2.5 Flash commonly prefaces its JSON with a prose sentence —
<em>"Here is the ProofDAG for this problem:"</em> — before the code fence.
The anchored regex required the fence to span the entire response string.
Any surrounding prose caused it to fail silently, passing the raw backtick
character to <code>JSON.parse</code>.</p>

<p>We replaced it with a three-pass extractor:</p>

<ol>
  <li>Find <code>&grave;&grave;&grave;json...&grave;&grave;&grave;</code> <em>anywhere</em> in the string (no anchors)</li>
  <li>Brace-balanced fallback: slice from the first <code>{</code> to the last <code>}</code></li>
  <li>Return as-is with a useful error</li>
</ol>

<p>We also added a regression test that mocks the exact production failure pattern.
This is a case where the test we didn't write cost us seven hours of GPU time.</p>

<h2>Math-First Triage</h2>

<p>One last structural issue: the Proof DAG planner was only invoked on
Attempt 2 and beyond. Attempt 1 always went directly to naive SA — the
ARCHITECT wasn't consulted at all. We moved the gate:</p>

<pre><code>// Before
if (attempt >= 2) { const dag = await formulateDAG(...); }
else { requestSearchPivot(...); }

// After
{ const dag = await formulateDAG(...); } // always; requestSearchPivot is catch-only</code></pre>

<p>The INITIAL TRIAGE directive — the Stage 1 prompt — was also rewritten. Instead
of "focus on direct combinatorial construction," it now reads:</p>

<blockquote>
  <em>Analyze the mathematical depth of the target goal. You have access to naive
  combinatorial search AND advanced structural frameworks. Do NOT blindly default
  to naive search. If the target is a notoriously difficult bound (like R(4,6) ≥ 36),
  naive search will fail. You are authorized and encouraged to start directly with an
  advanced structural reduction or continuous translation if the math warrants it.</em>
</blockquote>

<p>The ARCHITECT now receives this directive on Attempt 1, before any SA has run.
The engine is no longer required to fail first before asking for help.</p>

<h2>Where We Are</h2>

<p>After seven hours of running with a dead planner, the best energy the SA
workers found was <strong>E = 10</strong> — an improvement over the E = 12
floor from the previous search, and a new memetic seed persisted to disk.</p>

<p>What E = 10 means concretely: the current best candidate 2-coloring of K<sub>35</sub>
has 10 monochromatic cliques that shouldn't be there. Z3's LNS finisher confirmed
that the local neighborhood of the E = 10 graph has no valid coloring — the basin
is real, not a search artifact.</p>

<p>The search is running now, this time with the planner actually active. The next
interesting moment is when it hits its first pivot and the ARCHITECT has to decide:
more SA, or something stranger?</p>

<hr>

<p><em>Perqed is open source. <a href="https://github.com/bneb/perqed">Follow us on GitHub</a>
or <a href="/minutiae/">watch the agent think in real time</a>.</em></p>
`;
